      <H3><A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#2008-02-06"=20
      name=3D2008-02-06><FONT color=3D#660000>2008-02-06</FONT></A></H3>
      <DIV class=3Dposts><A name=3D8901274178393300662></A>
      <H2><FONT color=3D#000080><!-- 2004-09-02 -->OOXML-ODF: The =
Harmonization=20
      Hope Chest </FONT></H2>
      <P>
      <DIV style=3D"CLEAR: both"></DIV>
      <DIV class=3DwlWriterSmartContent=20
      =
id=3Dscid:0767317B-992E-4b12-91E0-4F059A8CECA8:3d7c4433-b94c-458d-9feb-a0=
3b64695718=20
      style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0px; DISPLAY: inline; PADDING-LEFT: 0px; =
FLOAT: none; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0px; MARGIN: 0px; PADDING-TOP: =
0px">Technorati=20
      Tags: <A href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/ODF" =
rel=3Dtag>ODF</A>, <A=20
      href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/OOXML" rel=3Dtag>OOXML</A>, <A=20
      href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/DIN" rel=3Dtag>DIN</A>, <A=20
      href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/Fraunhofer%20Institute"=20
      rel=3Dtag>Fraunhofer Institute</A>, <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/OOXML/ODF%20Translator%20Project"=20
      rel=3Dtag>OOXML/ODF Translator Project</A>, <A=20
      href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/open%20documents" =
rel=3Dtag>open=20
      documents</A>, <A=20
      href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/Office%20binary%20formats" =
rel=3Dtag>Office=20
      binary formats</A></DIV>
      <P>[<STRONG>Update 2008-03-06 (via <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/brian_jones/archive/2008/03/06/odf-editor-s=
peaks-out-in-support-of-open-xml.aspx">Brian=20
      Jones</A>):</STRONG> The DIN NIA 34 working group has raised its =
head=20
      above the waters.&nbsp; It is officially <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://www.nia.din.de/cmd?level=3Dtpl-artikel&amp;subcommitteeid=3D=
94340957&amp;contextid=3Dnia&amp;cmstextid=3D74610&amp;languageid=3Den">N=
A=20
      043-01-34-01 VT Working Group Translation 29500-26300</A>.&nbsp; =
They have=20
      published a schedule and the first working-paper draft is =
available for=20
      download.&nbsp; There is a terrific little graphic about the cases =
they=20
      want to understand.&nbsp; <STRIKE><EM>The copyright notice on this =

      document is what strikes me as the fatal flaw of ISO, ISO/IEC, and =
their=20
      business model.&nbsp; Why would I voluntarily lock up the fruits =
of my=20
      labors in such a prison?&nbsp; Would you?&nbsp; </EM>I'm =
sorry.&nbsp; This=20
      sets off my elitism-paternalism-bullshit detector.&nbsp; I'm sure =
it is=20
      simply thoughtless, but it's a <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/03/to-sir-with-respect.asp">level of =

      ritual</A> that does not invite my cooperation.&nbsp; I'll calm =
down=20
      later.&nbsp; Now I'm venting.</STRIKE>] [<STRONG>Update=20
      2008-03-07T20:13Z:</STRONG> I have calmed down and I am now =
embarrassed by=20
      my intemperate outburst.&nbsp; This is uncalled for.&nbsp; It =
demeans the=20
      worthy efforts of the DIN working group.&nbsp; I apologize.&nbsp; =
I will=20
      also apologize directly to the working group contact, and I will =
make a=20
      separate post on the lesson for me.]</P>
      <P>[<STRONG>Update 2008-02-16:</STRONG> Microsoft has delivered on =
its=20
      promise to ECMA TC45, originally reported by Brian Jones on =
January 16[<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#3">3</A>].&nbsp;=20
      The specifications for <EM>seven</EM> binary formats are placed =
under the=20
      Open Specification Promise and freely available for download [<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#14">14</A>].&nbsp;=20
      The SourceForge project, <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://sourceforge.net/projects/b2xtranslator">b2xTranslator</A>,=
=20
      has been established and its initial program of work has been =
posted [<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#15">15</A>].&nbsp;=20
      I am hopeful that this work and the conclusion of the DIS 29500 =
Ballot=20
      Resolution meeting will energize the DIN NIA 34 working group on =
OOXML-ODF=20
      translatability [<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#6">6</A>].]</P>
      <P>This post has four points:</P>
      <OL>
        <LI><A=20
        =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#1.0">Translatability=20
        Informs Harmonization</A><BR>Difficulty of translation is a =
rough=20
        indicator of the degree to which reconciliation of the formats =
is=20
        difficult.<BR>&nbsp;=20
        <LI><A=20
        =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#2.0">Models=20
        Limit Translation/Harmonization</A> <BR>There is no assurance =
that=20
        either format is universal enough, in the sense that it can =
faithfully=20
        express all documents of the other format.&nbsp; =
<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI><A=20
        =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#3.0">We=20
        Must Know the Differences</A>&nbsp;<BR>We need to know the =
severity of=20
        the model disparities and individual-feature differences before=20
        concluding how much useful harmonization is=20
        possible.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI><A=20
        =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#4.0">The=20
        Reality in the Punchbowl</A><BR>People do not deal with the file =
formats=20
        when creating office documents.&nbsp; The stored formats are =
below the=20
        level of office-worker attention and detail.&nbsp; Most people =
deal with=20
        their office-document software in an <EM>ad hoc</EM> way, using =
trial=20
        and error to obtain the appearance that is desired.&nbsp; =
Interchange=20
        among those using different (versions of) office-document =
software is=20
        dominated by these user practices.&nbsp; Common formats are not =
enough=20
        by themselves to ensure interoperability and faithful=20
      interchange.</LI></OL>
      <H3><A name=3D1.0>1. Translatability Informs =
Harmonization</A></H3>
      <P>Brian Jones has reported that there is a great deal of interest =
in=20
      harmonization of ODF and OOXML in some way [<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#1">1</A>].&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
      Subsequently, Brian reported on the ECMA response to ISO/IEC JTC1 =
DIS=20
      29500 (OOXML) ballot comments requesting harmonization [<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#2">2</A>],=20
      quoting from the ECMA response:=20
      <BLOCKQUOTE>
        <P>"Ecma believes that the work of the DIN (NIA-01-34) committee =
is=20
        essential to any harmonization effort. The work ... will enable =
the=20
        industry at large to understand the detailed differences between =
the=20
        formats. Based on this detailed understanding, the ODF and Open =
XML=20
        formats could be extended in the future in order to enable =
better=20
        sharing of information and allow future translations tools to =
provide=20
        even better translation and interoperability between the=20
      formats."</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
      <P>The announcement of the DIN initiative indicates that it will =
include=20
      the experience of the SourceForge OpenXML/ODF Translator Add-In =
project,=20
      and other efforts in its findings [<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#5">5</A>,=20
      <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#6">6</A>,=20
      <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#7">7</A>].=20

      <P>I agree, this is the best way we know to learn where the =
stumbling=20
      points are and what the prospects are for reconciling the document =

      models.&nbsp; I also appreciate that the ECMA response recognizes =
that=20
      current translation capabilities could be better with improved=20
      understanding of the formats, but no claim to perfect =
translatability is=20
      made.=20
      <H3><A name=3D2.0>2. Models Limit =
Translation/Harmonization</A></H3>
      <P>Cautious statements about the prospects for translation are =
also=20
      welcome.&nbsp;&nbsp; With regard to present capabilities, Jones =
quote of=20
      the ECMA response contains this earlier passage [<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#2">2</A>]:=20

      <BLOCKQUOTE>
        <P>"There are many translation tools already in existence that =
enable=20
        interoperability between different formats by providing=20
        <STRONG>useful</STRONG> translation capabilities between ODF, =
Open XML=20
        and UOF."</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
      <P>where that's my emphasis on "<STRONG>useful</STRONG>."</P>
      <P>I maintain that getting from "useful" through "even better" to=20
      "assured" is unlikely [<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#10">10</A>].&nbsp;=20
      </P>
      <P>I think it is reasonably-well understood that the architectures =
of=20
      OOXML and ODF documents are extremely different.&nbsp; There is =
great=20
      impact on how the format architectures are intended to be =
processed and=20
      how they map to tangible renderings of the document content.&nbsp; =
These=20
      details might be found to have common conceptual abstractions =
within which=20
      translation is reasonably-direct rewriting from one digital format =
to the=20
      other.&nbsp;&nbsp; There is reason for skepticism.&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
      Harmonization of terminology and metadata provides some important=20
      considerations [<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#9">9</A>]:</P>
      <BLOCKQUOTE>
        <P>"Existing solutions to the metadata harmonization issue are=20
        few=E2=80=94systems are either limited to a single =
specification, or implement=20
        ad-hoc solutions that only work in that particular environment. =
There=20
        are many examples of 'mappings' between specifications that =
provide=20
        partial solutions to the problem, but generally fail due to =
low-fidelity=20
        translations and lack of generality (i.e. the mapping only works =
for=20
        limited parts of specifications). Another solution is to create =
a=20
        top-level data model that encompasses the common aspects of all =
the=20
        specifications. This has proven to be feasible in relatively=20
        well-constrained domains . . . In the field of general metadata, =
where=20
        there is no such common ground, such an approach is =
substantially less=20
        likely to be successful."</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
      <P>I am skeptical that office-document formats provide a =
relatively=20
      well-constrained domain.&nbsp; Our optimism must be tempered by=20
      caution.</P>
      <H3><A name=3D3.0>3. We Must Know the Differences</A></H3>
      <P>I do agree that we need some concrete, specific undertaking to=20
      calibrate what kind of harmonization is possible as a practical=20
matter:</P>
      <UL>
        <LI>What are the features of ODF and OOXML that correspond in =
ways that=20
        can be preserved via useful translation and that could be a =
practical=20
        basis for harmonization?<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI>What are the places where ODF and OOXML are incommensurate =
in ways=20
        that can be reconciled by additions to one or the=20
        other?<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI>What is left as unreasonably difficult and how does that =
impact the=20
        users of software that relies on one format or the =
other?</LI></UL>
      <P>It will take serious effort to delineate these cases, and at =
the moment=20
      attention is on the Translation Working Group under DIN NIA-34 [<A =

      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#5">5</A>,=20
      <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#6">6</A>].&nbsp;=20
      <STRONG>Update:</STRONG> I am heartened to learn that there has =
been very=20
      serious analysis by public agencies of the Danish government [<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#12">12]</A>.&nbsp;=20
      <STRONG>Update Update:</STRONG> I have also unblocked my own =
thinking=20
      about an approach that might provide more concrete visibility on =
behalf of=20
      harmonization [<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#13">13</A>].</P>
      <H3><A name=3D4.0>4. The Reality in the Punchbowl</A></H3>
      <P>Meanwhile, Sam Hiser offers a different impression of the DIN =
effort=20
      [<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#4">4</A>]:</P>
      <BLOCKQUOTE>
        <P>"The ODF-to-OOXML <EM>harmonization</EM> effort being hosted =
by the=20
        German standards group, DIN, is Europe's best effort to resolve =
our=20
        <EM><A=20
        =
href=3D"http://fussnotes.typepad.com/plexnex/2007/04/mexican_standof.html=
">Mexican=20
        Standoff</A></EM> between Microsoft, Sun and IBM. Even though=20
        harmonization is <A=20
        =
href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/brian_jones/archive/2008/01/31/harmonizatio=
n-finding-the-differences.aspx">laughably=20
        complex</A> and <STRONG><EM>will not work unless the =
applications are=20
        harmonized too</EM></STRONG>, the best and brightest of Germany =
are left=20
        to hope for success."&nbsp; [<STRONG><EM>emphasis</EM></STRONG> =
mine:=20
        dh]</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
      <P>Although the mission of the German effort is translation =
(=C3=9Cbersetzung),=20
      not harmonization, I find there is a very important point that is =
not made=20
      often enough:&nbsp; </P>
      <UL>
        <LI>People write, read, and edit office documents with little, =
if any,=20
        understanding of the particular format that makes them =
persistent in=20
        digital form.&nbsp; The XML-based open formats do not change=20
        that.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI>People adapt to the software/device they are using by trial =
and=20
        error.&nbsp; We train ourselves to obtain the visible results =
that we=20
        want.&nbsp; Different people obtain superficially similar =
results by=20
        quite different means.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI>Even when someone has gone to the trouble to create style =
sheets,=20
        forms, macros, templates and other format-impacting aids, it is =
very=20
        loosey-goosey in practice.&nbsp; And it still does not require =
paying=20
        attention to the file format.&nbsp;&nbsp; </LI></UL>
      <P>I think that is a big deal. It is what people deal with. The =
formats=20
      are below everyone's direct attention and, while standardization =
and=20
      assurance of interchange is essential, it is insufficient, I =
think, with=20
      regard to what works for people who use products that "support" =
the=20
      formats.&nbsp; If interchange is the game, something else is =
required.</P>
      <H4>4.1 Living in a World of Appearances</H4>
      <P>Apart from the tab, space, enter, and back-tab keys, my =
personal=20
      control of layout is confined to an amazingly-prevalent set of =
toolbar=20
      icons:</P>
      <P align=3Dcenter><IMG alt=3D"Windows Live Writer 2008"=20
      =
src=3D"http://orcmid.com/viaggio/2008/xx/F08xx04-WLWMarkup.png">&nbsp; =
</P>
      <P align=3Dcenter><IMG alt=3D"Microsoft Office FrontPage 2003 =
(SP3)"=20
      =
src=3D"http://orcmid.com/viaggio/2008/xx/F08xx05-FP2003Markup.png"> </P>
      <P align=3Dcenter><IMG alt=3D"OpenOffice.org 2.3.0 Writer on =
Windows XP"=20
      =
src=3D"http://orcmid.com/viaggio/2008/xx/F08xx06-OOoWriterMarkup.png"> =
</P>
      <P align=3Dcenter><IMG alt=3D"Blogger.com Post Editor (on =
2008-02-06)"=20
      src=3D"http://orcmid.com/viaggio/2008/xx/F08xx07-BloggerEdit.png"> =
</P>
      <P align=3Dcenter><IMG alt=3D"Microsoft Office Word 2003 (SP3)"=20
      src=3D"http://orcmid.com/viaggio/2008/xx/F08xx08-Word2003.png"> =
</P>
      <P align=3Dcenter><IMG alt=3D"Microsoft Office Word 2007 (SP1)"=20
      src=3D"http://orcmid.com/viaggio/2008/xx/F08xx09-Word2007.png"> =
</P>
      <P align=3Dcenter><IMG alt=3D"MediaWiki entry editing toolbar"=20
      src=3D"http://orcmid.com/viaggio/2008/xx/F08xx10-MediaWiki.png"> =
</P>
      <P>For each of the HTML editors, I often edit the file format for =
desired=20
      effect.&nbsp; Usually the editors leave my markup alone enough for =
the=20
      result to be achieved.&nbsp; I am reminded of performing similar=20
      contortions with Borland Sprint, a document editor that employed a =

      plaintext markup scheme.&nbsp;=20
      <P>MediaWiki editing is also a form of direct markup, although my =
control=20
      over the HTML that is served up is indirect and mastered by=20
      trial-and-error post-and-revise exercises.&nbsp;=20
      <P>The important observation is that I use these features for the=20
      appearance that is produced and the tools and the symbols =
encourage me to=20
      do exactly that.&nbsp; I need not make any semantic distinctions =
while=20
      using the tools to achieve the formatting that serves my=20
      purposes.&nbsp;&nbsp; (I am disgruntled that some products replace =
indent=20
      and outdent with a =E2=80=9C=E2=80=9D toggle.&nbsp; I don't care =
that the element involved=20
      is tagged &lt;blockquote&gt; and don't get fancy with me.)=20
      <H4>4.2 For Users, It is the Computer Programs and What =
Happens</H4>
      <P><A></A>
      <P>People ask questions about software products and getting their =
job=20
      done, not formats.&nbsp; On the Massachusetts Information =
Technology=20
      Division site, all of the practical questions are for working =
between=20
      Microsoft Office and OpenOffice.org programs, not how to use the=20
      formats[<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#11">11</A>]:=20

      <BLOCKQUOTE>
        <P>"There are many features or ways your old office suite worked =
which=20
        are not accommodated in OpenOffice. Likewise, OpenOffice has =
many=20
        features not implemented in your old office suite. All users =
share=20
        different habits and rely upon a different subset of features to =
perform=20
        their daily tasks. While you may miss a few features that are=20
        significant to you, there is often a similar way in the new =
software to=20
        accomplish the same task; and users report that the new suite is =
fast to=20
        learn."</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
      <P>That is a great testament to the adaptability and =
resourcefulness of=20
      people, something that we are unable to endow in translators of =
any kind=20
      at this time.&nbsp; It is also not clear how this interactive =
dance fits=20
      into an interchange regimen, even among users of the same software =
product=20
      (release).=20
      <P>This passage shows how far the concerns in Massachusetts are =
from=20
      matters that might be governed by the respective formats:=20
      <BLOCKQUOTE>
        <P>"Yet there remain differences in the new [improved StarOffice =
and=20
        OpenOffice.org] tools which fail to offer improvement, and we =
would like=20
        users to feel empowered to report such discoveries to the =
mailing list."=20
        </P></BLOCKQUOTE>
      <P>Then there is this wonderful alibi about conversion failures:=20
      <BLOCKQUOTE>
        <P>"Even if the number of files likely to convert with trouble =
is low,=20
        anyone encountering file compatibility issues will experience=20
        frustration and inconvenience. In most cases still, corrupted =
files or=20
        those with characters slightly out of place can be fixed in the =
few=20
        minutes that it takes to curse one's luck.<BR>Users tend to =
blame the=20
        new office suite for the problems. Please keep in mind that =
engineers=20
        would be able to eliminate 99% of such conversion problems if =
the=20
        technical specifications of legacy file formats were to be=20
        published."</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
      <P>We'll see, won't we, especially since the legacy file formats =
technical=20
      specifications have been available for some time and will soon be =
easier=20
      to obtain [<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#3">3</A>].=20

      <P><STRONG>Update:</STRONG> I think there may be ways to offer =
products=20
      that are specifically geared to only using harmonious features of=20
      open-standard document formats [<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#13">13</A>].&nbsp;=20
      This would not require users to know or care about the formats and =
the=20
      ways that their documents comply, and the usual <EM>ad hoc</EM> =
behavior=20
      would work (so long as one does not have frustrating expectations =
of=20
      feature parity with all products).=20
