      <DIV class=3DblogComment><BR><A name=3D82756179868220940></A>Good =
heavens, is=20
      that all? This is pretty trivial. If it is the only example it is =
mildly=20
      ridiculous.<BR><BR>I agree that it is a bug, and easy to see how =
it got=20
      there. (I bet MSFT didn't have a test case for this until it came =
up in=20
      the comment about the Translator project.)<BR><BR>I figured there =
was a=20
      problem with Microsoft using more than what was in the spec, but =
this is a=20
      bug in the implementation of an initially-uncommon feature in the =
spec. It=20
      is a bug, though.<BR><BR>This is in the section of OOXML on =
versioning of=20
      the format itself where a new attribute introduced by someone =
making an=20
      extension can be tagged to be ignored, preserved, or deleted by an =
OOXML=20
      processor that doesn't understand the extension. <BR><BR>They were =
not=20
      honoring the instruction to preserve them. I wonder if this was =
fixed in=20
      Office 2007 Service Pack 1? I'll see if I can find the test file =
and=20
      check.<BR><BR>I'll also see if the spec. is solid around what =
should=20
      happen if the content of the element that has such an attribute is =

      edited.<BR>
      <DIV class=3Dbyline><A title=3D"permanent link"=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp#c82756179868220940">#</A>=20
