      class=3Ddelete-comment-icon>&nbsp;</SPAN></A></SPAN> </DIV>
      <DIV class=3DblogComment><BR><A =
name=3D1235882653159917547></A><B>Oops! Not a=20
      bug.</B><BR><BR>OK, I looked into ECMA-379, Part 5, clause 9.1.3, =
and it=20
      is not a bug. The relevant bits are on p.17, lines 5-23 just =
before clause=20
      9.1.3.1:<BR><BR>"Even in the presence of explicit preservation =
guidance in=20
      a markup specification, any markup editor might choose to discard =
together=20
      all ignored markup without regard to the presence of any =
PreserveElements=20
      or PreserveAttributes attribute. ... [M]arkup consumers shall =
always=20
      accept, but possibly disregard PreserveElements and =
PreserveAttributes=20
      attributes on any element."<BR><BR>It turns out that the =
PreservElements=20
      and PreserveAttributes stipulations are hints, and it is not =
mandatory to=20
      honor them.<BR><BR>So technically, as much as I don't like it =
myself, the=20
      behavior of Microsoft Office Word 2007 is acceptable either way. =
There are=20
      other nuances, but this is the bottom line of what ECMA-357 says =
on the=20
      topic.<BR>
